<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-224-982  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 224 982.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 12 1990 v24 n11 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer crime: ugly secret for business. (Part 1 of 4 )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer crime is on the rise and costing US industry billions ofdollars according to some estimates, but little is being done tostop it.andP;  There are two reasons why computer crime is difficult tohandle from a legal perspective: computer crime has never beenclearly defined, and businesses report only a small percentage ofknown crimes because they fear bad publicity.andP;  Without consensuson what a computer crime actually is, estimating its magnitude isdifficult.andP;  Computer crimes are also costly and time consuming toinvestigate and just do not take precedence over murders accordingto law officials.andP;  Public outcry could direct more attentiontowards the investigation and prosecution of computer crime cases.andO;Businesses need to help combat the occurrence of such crimes byincreasing computer security; the incentive to do so is becominggreater.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesSecurityTheft of InformationLaw EnforcementBusiness.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Victims or targets of computer crimes in 1986 and 1988. (graph)Different types of computer crime and percentage of occurrence.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>